    <h6><em>Cleaning and Compiling</em></h6>

    <p>This rich source of data also provided some challenges.  Specifically, the data did not exist in a single, aggregate file.  Because of the specific needs of this project, data had to be manually combined from several json files into one complete excel file for cleaning purposes.</p>

    <p>Arrests for each unique classification of crime were collected one by one as they only existed in separate files, the format was changed from json to csv, and then each was added to a single aggregate file.  Additionally, arrests for <em>all</em> crimes by month and year needed manual creation due to the fact that arrests across time only exists for unique crime types, for example, DUI.  This aggregate file was created by collecting each json file, converting it to a csv format, and then combining and cleaning via Excel.</p>



    <h6><em>Collapsing the Data</em></h6>
    
    <p>The data comprised of a wide range of offenses ranging from criminal mischief to murder.  Offenses were also often co-occurring; for example, gun offenses would often co-occur with drug offenses.  Additionally, some offenses were qualitatively the same but were recorded differently.  An example of this would be “reckless driving, dui” and “dui, reckless driving”.  For cases with no qualitative difference like the example above, the counts for these were combined.</p>

    <p>Upon examination, seven overarching themes to the arrest data appeared:  automobile related, cruelty and neglect, domestic and sexual offenses, drug/alcohol related, property offenses, general issues with law enforcement officers, and violent offenses.  Based on the type of offense, arrests were placed into one of these seven categories for simpler analyses.  For example, “murder” offenses were placed in the violence category.  For arrests where offenses co-occurred, the arrest was placed in one of the seven categories based on which offense was the most serious. As an example, a “drugs, license” offense was classified as an alcohol and drug related offense as “drugs” was considered the more serious of the two offenses.</p>


    <p>Definitions:</p>

    <ul>
        <li>Drug and alcohol: arrests where the most serious offense was related to substance use</li> 
        <li>Violence: arrests where the offense involved serious or potentially serious bodily harm to another individual</li> 
        <li>General Issues with Law Enforcement:  arrests that often resulted directly as a by-product of contact with police officers</li> 
        <li>Automobile Related:  arrests were an automobile was involved</li> 
        <li>Property: crimes against personal property that resulted in arrest</li> 
        <li>Domestic and Sexual: arrests as a result of sexual or physical harm against an intimate partner</li> 
        <li>Cruelty and Neglect:  crimes related to general abuse and neglect of “weaker” parties specifically children and animals</li> 
    </ul>

