    <h5><b>Conclusions</b></h5>

    <p>In sum, the descriptive analyses show a range in arrest data; from a wide range in arrests by team to the type of offense to fluctuations across time. Drug and alcohol related offenses constituted the majority of arrests by type while the Minnesota Vikings were the team leading the league in number of arrests.  Relative to time, arrests declined with the start of training camp and continued to remain low during the pre and regular seasons.</p>



    <h5><b>Next Steps</b></h5>

    <p>While the findings presented here are fun and informational, the applicability and usefulness appears limited.  Proposed next steps to improve the informative ability of the data would be to compare these arrest data to the general population of males of the same age during similar time frames.  With the findings as they are, it is not known if we should be troubled by these numbers.  Only with a comparison can we say that NFL players have more arrests than a similar sample of males from the general population and so be troubled.  Conversely, NFL players may have lower arrest rates when compared to the general population and if that is the case, these players should be encouraged to continue this pattern.</p>


